i386/tcg: Cyrix MediaGX 0F 3x Display Driver Instructions (Pinball 2000)

Per the Cyrix MediaGX Processor Data Book v2.0 (gxmdb_v20.pdf) sections
4.1.5 / 4.1.6 / Tables 4-6, 4-7, 4-8, the MediaGX defines four
documented opcodes in the second-byte-of-0F slot space:

  0F 3A  BB0_RESET   reset BLT-buffer-0 pointer to base    (NOT IMPL.,
                     collides with the SSSE3/SSE4 escape prefix slot)
  0F 3B  BB1_RESET   reset BLT-buffer-1 pointer to base
  0F 3C  CPU_WRITE   EBX = internal-CPU-register address ; EAX = data
  0F 3D  CPU_READ    EBX = internal-CPU-register address ; EAX = data

Documented internal-register address space (Table 4-8):

  L1_BB0_BASE     0xFFFFFF0Ch    BLT Buffer 0 base address
  L1_BB1_BASE     0xFFFFFF1Ch    BLT Buffer 1 base address
  L1_BB0_POINTER  0xFFFFFF2Ch    BLT Buffer 0 current pointer
  L1_BB1_POINTER  0xFFFFFF3Ch    BLT Buffer 1 current pointer
  PM_BASE         0xFFFFFF6Ch    Power management base address
  PM_MASK         0xFFFFFF7Ch    Power management address mask

Per section 4.1.6, these instructions are gated on GCR (index B8h)
bits[3:2] — SCRATCHPAD_SIZE — and should #UD when that field is zero.

  Datasheet: https://datasheets.chipdb.org/Cyrix/MediaGX/gxmdb_v20.pdf

------------------------------------------------------------------------
On-silicon behaviour observed in the Williams Pinball 2000 SWE1 v2.10
ROM (which shipped on real MediaGX silicon and was the behavioural
oracle for the Unicorn-era stub):

CPU_WRITE (0F 3C) does NOT only update the internal register selected
by EBX. As executed by real silicon (and required by the ROM), it ALSO
streams a (data, register-id) pair into scratchpad RAM at [DS:EDX] and
advances EDX by 8:

  [DS:EDX]      := EAX            ; 32-bit
  [DS:EDX + 4]  := EBX            ; 32-bit
  EDX           += 8

This is undocumented in §4.1.6 but is verified by static disassembly
of the SWE1 ROM at 0x002a232f / 0x002a233c — the ROM emits two 0F 3C
in succession with no `ADD EDX, 8` between them, and immediately after
the second 0F 3C copies EDX into EAX and writes a 16-bit colour key
(0x7C1F) through that pointer. With no CPU-side EDX increment, those
writes would clobber the first dword of the (data,id) pair instead of
landing past it. Mem-at-EDX dumps captured under instrumentation
confirm the scratchpad layout the ROM expects:

  +0x00 : data1 (e.g. 0x00000930   = BLT Buffer 0 base offset)
  +0x04 : addr1 (e.g. 0xFFFFFF0C   = L1_BB0_BASE register id)
  +0x08 : data2 (e.g. 0x00000400   = BLT Buffer 1 base offset)
  +0x0C : addr2 (e.g. 0xFFFFFF1C   = L1_BB1_BASE register id)
  +0x10 : 0x7C1F7C1F (colour key, written separately by the ROM)

The two BB-base writes (BB0_BASE := 0x930, BB1_BASE := 0x400) match
the canonical BLT-buffer addresses listed in Table 4-5 (§4.1.5):
"GX_BASE + 0x930  -> BLT Buffer 0 (1328 bytes)" and
"GX_BASE + 0x400  -> BLT Buffer 1 (1328 bytes)". So CPU_WRITE on real
silicon both updates the internal register AND mirrors the
(data, register-id) pair into the buffer pointed at by EDX, advancing
EDX so successive CPU_WRITEs build a packed buffer the BLT engine
later consumes.

This patch therefore implements both halves:

  (a) Internal-register model: writing CPU_WRITE(EBX, EAX) updates a
      sparse map keyed by EBX (BB0/BB1 BASE/POINTER, PM_BASE/PM_MASK,
      and any other 32-bit address future telemetry surfaces). CPU_READ
      reads that same map back into EAX.

  (b) Scratchpad pipeline: CPU_WRITE also stores (EAX, EBX) at
      [DS:EDX] / [DS:EDX+4] and advances EDX, mirroring the on-silicon
      side effect the ROM relies on.

  (c) BB1_RESET (0F 3B) sets L1_BB1_POINTER := L1_BB1_BASE.
      0F 3A BB0_RESET is NOT implemented because the slot is the SSE4
      3-byte-opcode escape prefix; SWE1 has not been observed to issue
      0F 3A so the SSE4 dispatch is preserved. If a real hit ever
      occurs the log+UD entry on slot 0x36/0x37/0x39/0x3F (and the
      future addition of an explicit 0F 3A gated decoder hook) will
      surface it.

------------------------------------------------------------------------
Gating

A runtime gate, p2k_mediagx_extensions_enabled (qemu/p2k-mediagx-gate.c),
is FALSE by default and set TRUE by the pinball2000 machine init. Stock
qemu-system-i386 (e.g. -M isapc) is unaffected: the helpers raise #UD
when the gate is FALSE, which preserves stock behaviour for these slots
that were #UD anyway.

The GCR[B8h] SCRATCHPAD_SIZE doc-mandated gate is NOT yet enforced; that
is a follow-up commit that bumps p2k-cyrix-ccr.c GCR value to encode a
non-zero scratchpad size.

The decoder additions live in slots 0x36, 0x37, 0x39, 0x3B, 0x3C, 0x3D,
0x3F. 0x38 and 0x3A are deliberately untouched (SSSE3 / SSE4 prefix
dispatch).

